{"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f4", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f4", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f4_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f4", "figure_label": "Figure 4.", "figure_caption": "Same as Figure&nbsp;2, for the GOODS-N field. North is up; east is to the left. Note that the scale of the <italic>F</italic>140<italic>W</italic> weight image differs from that of <italic>F</italic>125<italic>W</italic>&sol;<italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic>."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f5", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f5", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f5_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f5", "figure_label": "Figure 5.", "figure_caption": "Same as Figure&nbsp;2, for the GOODS-S field. North is up; east is to the left. Note that the scale of the <italic>F</italic>140<italic>W</italic> weight image differs from that of <italic>F</italic>125<italic>W</italic>&sol;<italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic> and that the deep HUDF regions are saturated on the exposure map scale shown here."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f6", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f6", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f6_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f6", "figure_label": "Figure 6.", "figure_caption": "Same as Figure&nbsp;2 for the UDS field. North is up; east is to the left. Note that the deep region of the image saturates on the scale shown for the exposure map."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f7", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f7", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f7_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f7", "figure_label": "Figure 7.", "figure_caption": "WFC3 science images are accompanied by three types of weight maps: inverse variance, exposure time, and number-of-exposures. We show an area of the COSMOS <italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic> mosaic (pointing COSMOS-V24&sol;COSMOS-V68) to illustrate the differences in the weight maps. Each cutout is &sim;2&farcm;5 on the side. A scale for each of the images is provided below the cutout. All three weight maps reflect masked and flagged pixels (satellite trails, the &ldquo;Death Star&rdquo;), but only the inverse variance map takes into account other error sources (flat field, background subtraction, read noise, dark current, etc.). All weight maps, as well as area maps that can be used for clustering analysis, are made available as part of the data release."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f8", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f8", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f8_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f8", "figure_label": "Figure 8.", "figure_caption": "Photometric filter set and two example SEDs for each of the five fields. The lower panels show the full set of filter curves used for the photometric catalog of each field, normalized to a maximum transmission of one. The upper two panels show the SEDs of two galaxies randomly chosen to demonstrate some of the variety of objects in the catalogs. The id and redshift of each object are shown in the top right corner. The black circles indicate the observed flux in each filter, the best-fit EAZY template spectra are shown in gray with the expected flux from the fit for each band in that catalog shown by the red circles. Some objects lie in areas of the image without coverage in one or more bands; in these cases only the predicted flux (red point) is shown. COSMOS and the GOODS-South field are particularly well sampled by the medium bands in the optical region, but there is excellent multi-wavelength coverage in all of the fields."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f9", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f9", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f9_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f9", "figure_label": "Figure 9.", "figure_caption": "Point-spread functions (PSFs) for the ACS&sol;<italic>F</italic>814<italic>W</italic> band and the WFC3&sol;<italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic> band in the AEGIS field. The construction of the PSFs is described in Section&nbsp;3.3. For each filter we show three stretch levels (panels 1&ndash;3 and 5&ndash;7) to expose the structure of the PSF: the core, the first Airy ring and the diffraction spikes. The images are normalized to a maximum value of one. The grayscale bars show the stretch for each panel. These are slightly different for ACS and WFC3 as a result of the different FWHMs (listed above the images). We also show the combined weight images for each PSF. The weight is largest in the center and lower at larger radii due to masking of neighboring objects. The ACS PSFs have lower weights in the central pixels because of cosmic ray rejection flagging the centers of stars. PSFs for all other bands and fields are shown in the Appendix."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f10", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f10", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f10_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f10", "figure_label": "Figure 10.", "figure_caption": "<italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic> growth curves. Upper panel: the fraction of light enclosed as a function of radius relative to the total light within 2&Prime;, <italic>f</italic>(<italic>r</italic>)&sol;<italic>f</italic>(2&Prime;), from the <italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic> PSF stamp of each field. The PSFs of the five fields are very consistent with each other. The gray points show the encircled energy as a function of aperture size, also normalized to 2&Prime;, from the WFC3 handbook. The empirical growth curves agree well with the theoretical expectation. Lower panel: the correction to total flux for a point source with a circularized Kron radius equal to the aperture radius on the <italic>x</italic>-axis, derived as the inverse of the growth curves in the upper panel (<italic>f</italic>(2&Prime;)&sol;<italic>f</italic>(<italic>r</italic>)). The minimum Kron radius is set to the aperture radius in which we measure colors, 0&farcs;35, giving rise to a maximum correction of &sim;1.21."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f11", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f11", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f11_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f11", "figure_label": "Figure 11.", "figure_caption": "Growth curves showing the fraction of light enclosed as a function of radius for each <italic>HST</italic> filter relative to the <italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic> growth curve in each of the five 3D-HST fields. The upper and lower panels show the growth curves before and after convolution to match the <italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic> PSF, respectively. Note the change in scale between the upper and the lower panels. The dashed lines in both panels represents a 1&percnt; difference. After PSF-matching, the resulting growth curves in all bands are consistent with the <italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic> PSF to well within 1&percnt; in each of the fields."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f12", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f12", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f12_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f12", "figure_label": "Figure 12.", "figure_caption": "Histograms of summed counts in different aperture sizes from empty regions throughout the image (left-hand panel) and the resultant noise-scaling as a function of aperture (right-hand panel) for the AEGIS <italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic> image. The measured &sigma;<sub>nmad</sub> are shown by the triangles. The solid line shows the power-law fit to the data, with the fit parameters given in the upper left. The dashed lines show the linear (&prop;<italic>N</italic>) and <italic>N</italic><sup>2</sup> scalings, which correspond to no correlation and perfect correlation between the pixels, respectively."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f13", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f13", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f13_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f13", "figure_label": "Figure 13.", "figure_caption": "Left panel: SExtractor&apos;s FLUX_RADIUS against total <italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic> magnitude for the GOODS-N field. Objects classified as point sources in the catalog are shown with red star symbols, galaxies and uncertain classifications (with <italic>H</italic><sub><italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic></sub> &gt; 25&nbsp;mag) as black symbols. The red dashed line, corresponding to the equation in the text, is used to make the selection. The red dotted line shows the magnitude limit of 25, beyond which the classification is deemed uncertain. The right panel demonstrates an alternate method of selecting point sources using the ratio of fluxes in a large and small aperture. The tightness of the stellar sequence in this ratio at brighter magnitudes (<italic>H</italic><sub><italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic></sub> &lsim; 24&nbsp;mag) allows for a more stringent classification, but the separation becomes less clear than the flux radius selection at fainter magnitudes. The flux ratio was used to select stars for the PSF-matching and kernel fitting. The symbols in the right panel correspond to the selection shown in the left panel; in general, the two methods agree well."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f14", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f14", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f14_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f14", "figure_label": "Figure 14.", "figure_caption": "Completeness fraction as a function of <italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic> magnitude determined by comparing the detections in an image with the typical depth of the CANDELS&sol;Wide images to the CANDELS&sol;Deep image of the same area within GOODS-South and the HUDF. The deep image is twice as deep as the shallow image, with approximately four times the exposure time. The counts in the HUDF have been scaled by a factor of nine to account for the difference in area. The solid black line shows the ratio of the counts in the shallow and deep areas. The fraction drops off faster relative to the HUDF, as seen from the dashed black line at <italic>H</italic><sub>160<italic>W</italic></sub> &gt; 25. The dotted lines show detection fractions of 90&percnt;, 75&percnt; and 50&percnt; with corresponding <italic>H</italic><sub>160<italic>W</italic></sub>-AUTO magnitudes of 25.1, 25.9 and 26.5&nbsp;mag relative to the deep image and 25.1, 25.8, and 26.2&nbsp;mag relative to the HUDF. The gray, green and red histograms show the number of objects detected in the deep, shallow and HUDF images, respectively, with the error bars representing Poisson errors."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f15", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f15", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f15_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f15", "figure_label": "Figure 15.", "figure_caption": "Number counts per unit area. The left-hand panel shows the number counts of galaxies with Poisson errors in each of the five fields as a function <italic>H</italic><sub><italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic></sub> total magnitude, with no correction for incompleteness. In the right-hand panel, the COSMOS and AEGIS number counts in the <italic>K</italic> band are compared to those from the NMBS survey (Whitaker et&nbsp;al. 2011) and UltraVISTA catalog from Muzzin et&nbsp;al. (2013). The error bars on all the data points represent Poisson errors. The agreement between 3D-HST and the NMBS for the AEGIS field is excellent. In COSMOS, we agree well with UltraVISTA over the full range where the ground-based survey is complete. The NMBS COSMOS number counts are somewhat higher, but agree well at the bright end, where all three surveys find an excess of bright galaxies compared to the AEGIS field."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f16", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f16", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f16_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f16", "figure_label": "Figure 16.", "figure_caption": "<italic>J</italic><sub><italic>F</italic>125<italic>W</italic></sub> &minus; <italic>H</italic><sub><italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic></sub> and <italic>H</italic><sub><italic>F</italic>140<italic>W</italic></sub>&minus; <italic>H</italic><sub><italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic></sub> colors vs. <italic>H</italic><sub><italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic></sub> magnitude for each of the five fields. Point sources are shown in red and extended sources in black. The medians for point sources and extended sources in the range 18 &lt; <italic>H</italic><sub><italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic></sub> &lt; 22 are labeled and shown by the red and blue lines, respectively. Objects with a SExtractor flag&nbsp;&gt; 0 have been excluded."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f17", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f17", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f17_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f17", "figure_label": "Figure 17.", "figure_caption": "<italic>J</italic><sub><italic>F</italic>125<italic>W</italic></sub> &minus; <italic>K</italic> vs. <italic>i</italic> &minus; <italic>K</italic> and <italic>J</italic><sub><italic>F</italic>125<italic>W</italic></sub> &minus; <italic>K</italic> vs. <italic>U</italic> &minus; <italic>J</italic><sub><italic>F</italic>125<italic>W</italic></sub> color&ndash;color diagrams for objects with <italic>K</italic> &lt; 24.5&nbsp;mag and <italic>H</italic><sub><italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic></sub> &lt; 25&nbsp;mag in each of the five fields. Point sources are shown in red and extended sources in black. Objects with a SExtractor flag&nbsp;&gt; 0 have been excluded. Note that in the GOODS-N field, we use the <italic>F</italic>775<italic>W</italic> filter for the <italic>i</italic>-band, while the other fields use the <italic>F</italic>814<italic>W</italic> filter. The <italic>U</italic>-band and <italic>K</italic>-band filters also differ from field to field. The distributions are consistent with each other. The stellar locus can be clearly identified in color&ndash;color space."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f18", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f18", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f18_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f18", "figure_label": "Figure 18.", "figure_caption": "Ratio of aperture flux to total catalog flux as a function of aperture radius in each field and WFC3 band. Sources were selected to have S&sol;N&nbsp;&gt; 50. In each case few hundred extended sources were chosen randomly from the catalog with the requirement that they satisfy use<sub>phot</sub> = 1 in addition to the S&sol;N cut. Point sources are shown in red and extended sources in black. The median values for point sources and extended sources are shown by the large stars and filled circles, respectively. The agreement between the derived total catalog fluxes and the direct measurements of flux in 3&Prime; apertures are good. The measurements are consistent across the fields."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f19", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f19", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f19_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f19", "figure_label": "Figure 19.", "figure_caption": "Comparison of the 3D-HST WFC3 total magnitudes to total magnitudes from morphological fits with GALFIT measured on the same images (see van der Wel et&nbsp;al. 2012). Objects with a good fit from GALFIT (GALFIT flag = 0) are shown dark gray, while objects with a suspicious fit (GALFIT flag = 1) are shown in light gray. Objects with a bad fit from GALFIT (GALFIT flag &gt;1), a 3D-HST use_phot flag = 0 or SExtractor flags &ges;2 have been excluded from the comparison. The running medians for GALFIT flag = 0 and flag = 1 objects are shown in red and blue, respectively. The contour levels are 5&percnt;, 10&percnt;, 25&percnt;, 50&percnt; and 75&percnt; of the maximum density."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f20", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f20", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f20_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f20", "figure_label": "Figure 20.", "figure_caption": "Difference between total magnitudes from GALFIT and 3D-HST in two WFC3 bands for 21 &lt; <italic>H</italic><sub><italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic></sub> &lt; 24. The upper (lower) panels compare the <italic>J</italic><sub>F125W</sub> (<italic>H</italic><sub>F140W</sub>) and the <italic>H</italic><sub>F160W</sub> magnitude differences. Only objects with good GALFIT fits (GALFIT flag = 0) and 3DHST use_phot = 1 are included. The medians are shown with a star symbol and labelled in the upper left corner of each plot. The contour levels represent 2&percnt;, 10&percnt;, 20&percnt; and 50&percnt; of the maximum density. The differences are correlated and smallest in <italic>H</italic><sub>F160W</sub>."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f21", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f21", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f21_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f21", "figure_label": "Figure 21.", "figure_caption": "<italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic> error distributions in each of the five fields. The units are such that AB = 25 &minus; log&thinsp;(value). Objects with use_phot = 0 are shown in blue if they are extended or in red if they are point sources (star_flag = 1). Galaxies defined with use_phot = 1 are shown in black. Upper panels: <italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic> errors within an aperture of 0&farcs;7 vs. magnitude. The variable depths across each mosaic give rise to the discrete levels. GOODS-S is the deepest image with aperture errors reaching the lowest values, while COSMOS is the shallowest field on average. Middle panels: total <italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic> error vs. magnitude, as determined by scaling the noise within empty apertures to the aperture size of the circularized Kron radius of each object and making a correction to total as described in the text. Lowest panels: <italic>F</italic>160<italic>W</italic> (total) signal to noise vs. magnitude. Point sources have the highest S&sol;N at a given magnitude, while objects that should be excluded from analysis because they have low weight (and correspondingly large errors) form the lower envelope of the distribution."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs499030f22", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs499030f22", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/24/apjs499030f22_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs499030f22", "figure_label": "Figure 22.", "figure_caption": "Comparison of the photometric uncertainties to the actual scatter in the data. For each filter in each field, the observed fluxes were 