always &lt;0.8), and &ldquo;non-selective&rdquo; data displaying slopes &lsim; 0.4, seems to support our classifications detailed in Section&nbsp;3.3.2. Errors in individual MS slope measurements have been taken from their respective studies when available."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs498241f2", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs498241f2", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/15/apjs498241f2_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs498241f2", "figure_label": "Figure 2.", "figure_caption": "log&thinsp;&psi; vs. <italic>t</italic> for log&thinsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>&ast;</sub> &equals; 10.5 before (left) and after (right) we introduce our &minus;0.1&nbsp;dex stacking correction to convert between the mean and median in log space and the (1 &plus; <italic>z</italic>)<sup>&minus;0.8</sup> calibration offset to the radio data, calculated using the best-fit MS relations from each of the 25 studies listed in Table&nbsp;3. Data points are colored based on the SFR indicators they primarily use: blue = UV, purple = UV+IR, red = IR, green = emission lines, yellow = SED fitting, black = radio. Stacked data in all panels are indicated by hollow points, while non-stacked data are filled. The horizontal errors indicate the redshift range spanned by each particular observation, while the vertical errors are the &ldquo;true&rdquo; scatter about each MS observation (see Section&nbsp;4.1.2). For stacked data, the plotted true scatters are derived assuming a fiducial intrinsic scatter of 0.3&nbsp;dex. The best fits excluding (pre-&ldquo;correction&rdquo;; dotted line) and including (post-&ldquo;correction&rdquo;; solid line) the radio data are overplotted in each panel. The marked difference in stacked radio SFR observations at higher redshifts, their excellent agreement following our corrections, and the small effect these new radio SFRs have on the fit all suggest we are observing a real systematic difference between radio SFRs as compared to other SFR indicators."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs498241f3", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs498241f3", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/15/apjs498241f3_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs498241f3", "figure_label": "Figure 3.", "figure_caption": "log&thinsp;&psi; vs. <italic>t</italic> for log&thinsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>&ast;</sub> &equals; (9.5, 10.0, 10.5, 11.0), calculated using the best-fit MS relations from each of the 25 studies listed in Table&nbsp;3 and plotted using the same color&sol;symbol scheme as Figure&nbsp;1. Data from E11 (which is excluded from our fits) are plotted in green. The best fits (excluding non-selective data; see Figure&nbsp;1 and Section&nbsp;4) for a given mass are plotted as red dashed lines."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs498241f4", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs498241f4", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/15/apjs498241f4_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs498241f4", "figure_label": "Figure 4.", "figure_caption": "log&thinsp;&psi; vs. <italic>t</italic> for log&thinsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>&ast;</sub> &equals; (9.5, 10.0, 10.5, 11.0), calculated using the best-fit MS relations from each of the 25 studies listed in Table&nbsp;3 and plotted using the same color&sol;symbol scheme as Figure&nbsp;2. The best fits (excluding non-selective data; see Figure&nbsp;1 and Section&nbsp;4) for a given mass are plotted as red dashed lines."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs498241f5", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs498241f5", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/15/apjs498241f5_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs498241f5", "figure_label": "Figure 5.", "figure_caption": "Similar to Figure&nbsp;4, but here redshift evolution (shown by the best-fit relations) is illustrated for various (sub)samples at log&thinsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>&ast;</sub> &equals; 10.5. The dotted black, dashed red, and long dashed blue lines indicate the best-fit relations (excluding the first and last 2&nbsp;Gyr of data) to all SFG observations, &ldquo;mixed&rdquo; observations only, and &ldquo;bluer&rdquo; observations only. The best-fit relation to bluer observations including low-<italic>z</italic> SDSS data (dashed cyan) is shown for contrast. As can be seen in our bluer low-<italic>z</italic> fit, the time evolution of the SFR is significantly reduced if we restrict ourselves to observations biased toward bluer studies only, in good agreement with Karim et&nbsp;al. (2011). There is good agreement among all three fits when low-<italic>z</italic> (and high-<italic>z</italic>) data has been excluded."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs498241f6", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs498241f6", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/15/apjs498241f6_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs498241f6", "figure_label": "Figure 6.", "figure_caption": "Scatter observed for the subset of non-stacked data before (blue) and after (green) our deconvolution process, plotted as a function of the width of the respective time bin it encompasses (&Delta;<italic>t</italic>). The best-fit linear trends are overplotted (dashed lines). Studies with small sample sizes (<italic>N</italic> &lt; 250) or that have been selected via <italic>sBzK</italic> have been excluded from the fit, as well as the results of S09, So14, and C14 (due to the former&apos;s &sigma;-clipped fit and the latter two&apos;s differing selection criteria, respectively). Our deconvolution process has the largest effects on data observed in the largest time bins, and removes any trends with time to within the fitted errors (slope of 0.002&thinsp; &plusmn; &thinsp;0.005&nbsp;dex&nbsp;per&nbsp;Gyr)."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs498241f7", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs498241f7", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/15/apjs498241f7_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs498241f7", "figure_label": "Figure 7.", "figure_caption": "&ldquo;True&rdquo; scatter about the MS as a function of time, with red and blue points representative for mixed and bluer selection methods, cyan points for <italic>sBzK</italic> studies, and purple points indicating samples with less than 250 galaxies. The prevalence of <italic>sBzK</italic> points well below the majority of the data suggests that it is somehow &ldquo;missing&rdquo; a significant portion of SFGs (see Section&nbsp;3.3.3), while the lower scatters among smaller samples indicates the prevalence of selection effects. The best-fit relations for each respective selection method, excluding both of these categories, are plotted as dashed lines in their respective colors. Given the uncertainties, this seems to indicate on average a constant MS scatter over the majority of the age of the universe."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs498241f8", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs498241f8", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/15/apjs498241f8_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs498241f8", "figure_label": "Figure 8.", "figure_caption": "Several of our &ldquo;consensus&rdquo; MS relations taken from our best fit to observations from the literature (see Section&nbsp;5.1) plotted at several given redshifts. The widths of the distributions are taken to be the &ldquo;true&rdquo; scatters (&plusmn;0.2&nbsp;dex) rather than the likely observed scatters (&sim;0.3&nbsp;dex) for improved clarity, and the mass bounds are taken directly from the fit. The changing MS slope and &sim;2 orders of magnitude evolution in SFR at fixed mass from <italic>z</italic> &equals; 4 to 0 are easily visible. As the first and last 2&nbsp;Gyr of data are not included in the fit, the <italic>z</italic> &equals; 0 and <italic>z</italic> &equals; 4 slopes should be viewed as predictions of high-&sol;low-<italic>z</italic> MS relations rather than simply best fits to data available at those redshifts (which would tend to fit well by default)."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs498241f9", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs498241f9", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/15/apjs498241f9_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs498241f9", "figure_label": "Figure 9.", "figure_caption": "Calculated log&thinsp;&psi; tracks for galaxies that strictly evolve along the MS with final stellar masses of 10<sup>10</sup>&thinsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>&sun;</sub> at the present day, assuming direct SFR-to-<italic>M</italic><sub>&ast;</sub> growth (black), a zeroth order &ldquo;return rate&rdquo; correction (from stellar mass to gas mass) to account for mass loss from young, massive stars (blue), and an additional first-order correction (accurate to within a few percent of the final mass) to account for mass loss from older stellar populations (red). Both stellar mass loss prescriptions are taken from Leitner &amp; Kravtsov (2011) and Leitner (2012) and assume a Chabrier IMF (functionally equivalent to a Kroupa IMF). Initial seed masses of 10<sup>7</sup>&thinsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>&sun;</sub> are assumed. Dashed lines indicate the return rate for the given correction as a function of time, and dash-dotted lines indicate the mass growth the galaxy over the same period."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs498241f10", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs498241f10", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/15/apjs498241f10_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs498241f10", "figure_label": "Figure 10.", "figure_caption": "As Figure&nbsp;9, but for &psi;. The magnitude of the peak for galaxies including first-order approximations for stellar mass loss can more easily be seen. In addition, a mix of &ldquo;fast growth&rdquo; (i.e., power-law rising), approximately constant, and exponentially declining SFH over time are clearly visible, implying that delayed-&tau; models (which naturally include all three phases) provide the most accurate parameterizations of typical MS SFHs."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs498241f11", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs498241f11", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/15/apjs498241f11_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs498241f11", "figure_label": "Figure 11.", "figure_caption": "As Figure&nbsp;9, but for the sSFR. As can be seen, the sSFR (i.e., the inverse growth timescale of a galaxy) decreases over time to the present day values in an approximately linear fashion after an initially steep decline. Including stellar mass loss prescriptions leads to a more gradual decline in the sSFR (in log space) compared to the direct SFR-to-mass growth."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs498241f12", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs498241f12", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/214/2/15/apjs498241f12_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs498241f12", "figure_label": "Figure 12.", "figure_caption": "Comparison of the derived <italic>M</italic><sub>&ast;</sub>&ndash;&psi; relation using (a) well-fit photometric redshifts (&eta; &lt; 0.15; light blue) and (b) poorly fit photometric redshifts (&eta; &gt; 0.15; red) from the GOODS-MUSIC catalog. The best-fit star-forming main sequence has a similar slope of &alpha; &sim; 0.6 in both cases, although the &ldquo;bad&rdquo; photo-<italic>z</italic> sample displays slightly more scatter."}]	2015-03-19 11:49:37.753969
