usmn; 0.03&thinsp;<italic>R</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>, Mp = 2.71 &plusmn; 1.8&thinsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489847f39", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489847f39", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/20/apjs489847f39_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489847f39", "figure_label": "Figure 39.", "figure_caption": "Upper left: seeing-limited image for Kepler-407 (KOI-1442). Upper right: adaptive optics image from Keck NIRC2. Middle: limiting magnitudes of companion stars from Speckle and AO imaging. Lower left and lower right: same as Figure&nbsp;1, but for Kepler-407. No secondary lines from a companion are detected. Any companion brighter than 0.5&percnt; the brightness (<italic>V</italic> band) of the primary would have been detected."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489847f40", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489847f40", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/20/apjs489847f40_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489847f40", "figure_label": "Figure 40.", "figure_caption": "Top: RV vs. time for Kepler-407 (KOI-1442). Lower left: phase-folded <italic>Kepler</italic> photometry for the transiting planet. Lower right: phase-folded radial velocities for each planet. The blue points represent binned RVs near quadrature, same as Figure&nbsp;2. Kepler-407b: Rp = 1.07 &plusmn; 0.02&thinsp;<italic>R</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>, Mp = 0.06 &plusmn; 1.2&thinsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>. Kepler-407c: Rp = NA, Mp = 4000 &plusmn; 2000&thinsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>, period = 3000 &plusmn; 500d. Kepler-407 could be a planet, brown dwarf, or a star, depending on the inclination of the orbit."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489847f41", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489847f41", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/20/apjs489847f41_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489847f41", "figure_label": "Figure 41.", "figure_caption": "Upper left: seeing-limited image for KOI-1612. Upper right: adaptive optics image. Middle: limiting magnitudes of companion stars found with Speckle and AO imaging. Lower left and lower right: same as Figure&nbsp;1, but for KOI-1612. No companions are detected. Any companion brighter than 0.5&percnt; the brightness (<italic>V</italic> band) of the primary would have been detected."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489847f42", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489847f42", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/20/apjs489847f42_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489847f42", "figure_label": "Figure 42.", "figure_caption": "Top: RV vs. time for KOI-1612. Middle: phase-folded radial velocities for each planet. Bottom: phase-folded <italic>Kepler</italic> photometry for the planet. The blue points represent binned RVs near quadrature, same as Figure&nbsp;2. KOI-1612.01: Rp = 0.82 &plusmn; 0.03&thinsp;<italic>R</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>, Mp = 0.48 &plusmn; 3.2&thinsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489847f43", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489847f43", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/20/apjs489847f43_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489847f43", "figure_label": "Figure 43.", "figure_caption": "Upper left: seeing-limited image for Kepler-409b (KOI-1925). Upper right: adaptive optics image. Middle: limiting magnitudes of companion stars found with Speckle and AO imaging. Lower left and lower right: same as Figure&nbsp;1, but for Kepler-409. No companions are detected. Any companion brighter than 0.5&percnt; the brightness (<italic>V</italic> band) of the primary would have been detected."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489847f44", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489847f44", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/20/apjs489847f44_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489847f44", "figure_label": "Figure 44.", "figure_caption": "Top: RV vs. time for Kepler-409 (KOI-1925). Middle: phase-folded radial velocities for each planet. Bottom: phase-folded <italic>Kepler</italic> photometry for each planet. The blue points represent binned RVs near quadrature, same as Figure&nbsp;2. Kepler-409b: Rp = 1.19 &plusmn; 0.03&thinsp;<italic>R</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>, Mp = 2.69 &plusmn; 6.2&thinsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489847f45", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489847f45", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/20/apjs489847f45_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489847f45", "figure_label": "Figure 45.", "figure_caption": "Histogram of the radii of the 42 transiting planets studied here, most of which are smaller than 3&thinsp;<italic>R</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>, with 6 greater than 3&thinsp;<italic>R</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>. The radii were determined from full models of the transit light curves, and stellar radii coming from analysis of high-resolution spectra and, for 11 cases, asteroseismological analysis."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489847f46", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489847f46", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/20/apjs489847f46_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489847f46", "figure_label": "Figure 46.", "figure_caption": "Histogram of the masses of the 42 transiting planets studied here. The mass determinations stem from the multiple RV measurements of the host star and the constrained orbital period and measured time of transit from the <italic>Kepler</italic> photometry. Circular orbits were assumed in all cases. Mass determinations represent the peak of the posterior mass distribution from the MCMC analysis of the RVs. For four planets, fluctuations (errors) in the RVs happen to yield a peak in the posterior mass distribution that resides at a negative mass (<italic>K</italic> is negative, given the frozen orbital phase). While unphysical, the negative masses offer an unbiased statistical balance against the fluctuations that yield overly positive masses. The masses span a range up to 25&thinsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>. See Figure&nbsp;49 for the well determined planet masses."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489847f47", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489847f47", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/20/apjs489847f47_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489847f47", "figure_label": "Figure 47.", "figure_caption": "Histogram of the densities of the 42 transiting planets studied here. Four values of density are negative, due to negative masses (See Figure&nbsp;46), three being offscale. The physical planet densities span a range from below unity to 15&nbsp;g&nbsp;cm<sup>&minus;3</sup>. As each density is the mode of a broad posterior distribution, caution should be exercised in interpreting the histogram. See Figure&nbsp;51 for the well-measured density measurements."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489847f48", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489847f48", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/20/apjs489847f48_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489847f48", "figure_label": "Figure 48.", "figure_caption": "Planet mass vs. radius for the 16 transiting planets studied here having a mass measured at the 2&sigma; confidence level or better. Planet mass increases systematically with increasing radius. The weighted, linear fit to the planet masses and radii is, <italic>M</italic> &equals; 3.28<italic>R</italic> &plus; 0.79 (with <italic>M</italic> and <italic>R</italic> in Earth units), for planet radii in the range 1&ndash;5.5&thinsp;<italic>R</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>. The monotonic relationship is consistent with a predominantly rocky composition for planets smaller than &sim;2&thinsp;<italic>R</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>, and an increasing contribution of low-density material (probably H, He, or light molecules) for larger planets. The present data do not warrant more than a linear relationship, but see Weiss &amp; Marcy (2013) and L. Rogers et&nbsp;al. (2014, in preparation)."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489847f49", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489847f49", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/20/apjs489847f49_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489847f49", "figure_label": "Figure 49.", "figure_caption": "Planet mass vs. radius for both the 16 transiting planets having a 2&sigma; mass measurement, along with 14 upper limits to the masses of the remaining planets. The best-fit linear relation between planet mass and radius is, <italic>M</italic> &equals; 3.28<italic>R</italic> &plus; 0.79 (with <italic>M</italic> and <italic>R</italic> in Earth units), for planet radii in the range 1&ndash;5.5&thinsp;<italic>R</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>. The upper limits are consistent with the linear trend in M&nbsp;vs. R found from the 16 detections and their scatter. These upper limits are consistent with mass increasing systematically with radius, as in Figure&nbsp;48 Some planets appear to have masses below the linear fit at the 2&sigma; level, indicating that some of them contain more volatile material than average for their radius, i.e., diversity of composition for a given radius. See Weiss &amp; Marcy (2013) and L. Rogers et&nbsp;al. (2014, in preparation) for further statistical treatment. The 12 planets with an uncertainty in density greater than 6.5&nbsp;g&nbsp;cm<sup>&minus;3</sup> were excluded from this plot."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489847f50", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489847f50", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/20/apjs489847f50_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489847f50", "figure_label": "Figure 50.", "figure_caption": "Planet mass vs. radius for 30 transiting planets measured here. The plotted masses represent the peak of the posterior distribution of the planet masses. Most peaks reside at positive masses, but RV fluctuations occasionally yield a peak at negative masses, clearly representing non-detections. We retain the negative masses to avoid Lutz&ndash;Kelker-type bias toward positive masses. The best-fit linear relation is <italic>M</italic> &equals; 4.24<italic>R</italic> &minus; 2.29 (in Earth units) for planet radii in the range 1&ndash;5.5&thinsp;<italic>R</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>, including negative masses in the fit. Of the 42 transiting planets studied here, we excluded from this plot the 12 transiting planets having a density uncertainty greater than 6.5&nbsp;g&nbsp;cm<sup>&minus;3</sup> (but included all mass measurements, even if less than a 2&sigma; detection)."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489847f51", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489847f51", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/20/apjs489847f51_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489847f51", "figure_label": "Figure 51.", "figure_caption": "Planet density vs. radius for all 30 transiting planets having an uncertainty in density less than 6.5&nbsp;g&nbsp;cm<sup>&minus;3</sup>. Planet density declines systematically with increasing planet radius in the domain of 1.0&ndash;5.5&thinsp;<italic>R</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>. Increasing planet radius apparently is associated with increasing amounts of low-density material, presumably H, He, and light molecules. For an analysis of density vs. radius for all known planets, see Weiss &amp; Marcy (2013) and L. Rogers et&nbsp;al. 2014 (in preparation)."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489847f52", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489847f52", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/20/apjs489847f52_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489847f52", "figure_label": "Figure 52.", "figure_caption": "Planet density vs. planet mass for the 30 transiting planets measured here. Planet density appears to increase from 1 to &sim;6&thinsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>, and then decline from &sim;6&ndash;25&thinsp;<italic>R</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub>, with large scatter in density. This behavior is consistent with planets of 0&ndash;6&thinsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub> having a mostly rocky interior experiencing increased gravitational compression (or greater iron&sol;nickel content). The decline in density for planet masses, <italic>M</italic> &gt; 6&thinsp;<italic>M</italic><sub>&oplus;</sub> indicates increasing amounts of low-density material, presumably H, He, and light molecules, with increasing planet mass. The scatter in planet density, at a given planet mass, indicates a diversity of chemical composition at a given mass, with different admixtures of iron, rock, and light elements."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489847f53", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489847f53", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/20/apjs489847f53_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489847f53", "figure_label": "Figure 53.", "figure_caption": "Planet radius vs. orbital period for 30 well-measured transiting planets. Planet radii are not strongly correlated with orbital period in the present sample."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489847f54", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489847f54", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/20/apjs489847f54_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489847f54", "figure_label": "Figure 54.", "figure_caption": "Planet density vs. orbital period for 30 well-measured transiting planets. Planet density is not strongly correlated with orbital period. There is no convincing evidence that the density, and hence planet composition, is a strong function of orbital distance, out to periods of 45&nbsp;days. But mass detection biases may affect this interpretation."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489847f55", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489847f55", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/20/apjs489847f55_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489847f55", "figure_label": "Figure 55.", "figure_caption": "Histogram of impact parameters, <italic>b</italic>, for all 42 transiting planets studied here. The impact parameter is derived from a self-consistent transiting-planet model fit to the photometry and RVs, with constraints on the stellar radius from spectroscopy and asteroseismology. The roughly uniform distribution of impact parameters, from 0 to 1, is consistent with the geometrical expectation of a random distribution of orbital tilt angles relative to our line of sight, leading to a uniform distribution of impact parameters, <italic>b</italic>."}]	2015-03-19 11:49:39.600833
20	2014ApJS..210...21C	10.1088/0067-0049/210/2/21	IOP	f	[{"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489879f1", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489879f1", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/21/apjs489879f1_tb.gif", "format": "gif"}], "figure_id": "apjs489879f1", "figure_label": "Figure 1.", "figure_caption": "Left: scattering efficiency <italic>Q<sub>s</sub></italic> of a particle with refractive indices <italic>n<sub>r</sub></italic> &equals; 1.33,&thinsp;<italic>n<sub>i</sub></italic> &equals; 0 as a function of its optical size <italic>x</italic> &equals; 2&pi;<italic>a</italic>&sol;&lambda; using Mie theory (figure reproduced directly from Hansen &amp; Travis (1974), by permission, where particle radius = <italic>a</italic>). The parameter <italic>b</italic> varies the width of the size distribution; as the size distribution gets broad, exotic ripples dues to interference average out and vanish. Right: dependence on the optical size and material properties of the scattering asymmetry parameter <italic>g</italic> &equals; &lang;cos&thinsp;&Theta;&rang;, for narrow size distributions of different optical size. Note there are essentially two well-defined regimes in <italic>n<sub>i</sub></italic>. Figure&nbsp;2 gives more detail on how <italic>g</italic> varies with <italic>x</italic>."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489879f2", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489879f2", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/21/apjs489879f2_tb.gif", "format": "gif"}], "figure_id": "apjs489879f2", "figure_label": "Figure 2.", "figure_caption": "Variation of <italic>g</italic> &equals; &lang;cos&thinsp;&Theta;&rang; (&alpha; &equals; &Theta; and <italic>a</italic> &equals; <italic>r</italic> in the notation of HT), and <italic>x</italic> &equals; 2&pi;<italic>r</italic>&sol;&lambda;, for a range of <italic>n<sub>r</sub></italic>. It is easy to show that the dependence in the steep transition region is <italic>g</italic>&prop;<italic>x</italic><sup>2</sup>, while the large-<italic>x</italic> asymptote and transition point depend on <italic>n<sub>r</sub></italic>. With an eye towards the Garnett EMT value of <italic>n<sub>r</sub></italic> for our cosmic mixture (1.7&ndash;2.1), we have chosen the single function <italic>g</italic> &equals; 0.7(<italic>x</italic>&sol;3)<sup>2</sup> to represent all particles and materials. Figure reproduced from HT Figure&nbsp;12, by permission."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489879f3", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489879f3", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/21/apjs489879f3_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489879f3", "figure_label": "Figure 3.", "figure_caption": "Real (left) and imaginary (right) indices as used in our code, representing a number of common materials, taken directly from Pollack et&nbsp;al. (1994). Black long dashed line: water ice; cyan dash&ndash;dotted line: silicates; green short dashed line: iron sulfide; blue dotted line: iron metal; red long dash&ndash;dotted line: organics. For simplicity we have used only one of Pollack et&nbsp;al.&apos;s two varieties of silicates (pyroxene) as they both have similar properties, and only one variety of organics (the two of Pollack et&nbsp;al. 1994 had the same refractive indices but two different evaporation temperatures were assumed).\\n(A color version and supplemental data of this figure are available in the <inline-supplementary-material xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" content-type=\\"Supplemental data\\" xlink:title=\\"Figure 3\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs489879f3.tar.gz\\">online</inline-supplementary-material> journal.)"}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489879f4", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489879f4", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/21/apjs489879f4_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489879f4", "figure_label": "Figure 4.", "figure_caption": "Comparison with Mie theory of our mean extinction efficiency <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $Q^{\\\\prime }_{ej}(\\\\lambda)$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs489879ieqn6.gif\\"/></inline-formula> for five pure materials, averaged and weighted over the Pollack et&nbsp;al. (1994) size distribution (see Section&nbsp;4.1). Our model results are shown in solid curves and Mie calculations are shown in dashed curves. The lower right panel is the abundance-weighted average value <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $Q^{\\\\prime }_e(\\\\lambda)$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs489879ieqn7.gif\\"/></inline-formula>. The solid curve in the iron panel includes an (imperfect) correction for magnetic dipole effects (Appendix&nbsp;B), and the dotted (<italic>Q<sub>a</sub></italic>) and dot-dash (<italic>Q<sub>s</sub></italic>) curves do not. Actually, all the solid curves incorporate this correction term, but it makes a difference only for iron."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489879f5", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489879f5", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/21/apjs489879f5_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489879f5", "figure_label": "Figure 5.", "figure_caption": "Comparison between the Rosseland mean opacities as determined here, with much more elaborate full Mie scattering calculations (see text for discussion). The Pollack model has silicates, organics, and water ice evaporating at slightly different temperatures than assumed here (in fact they are a function of pressure); these are easily adjusted if desired."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489879f6", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489879f6", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/21/apjs489879f6_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489879f6", "figure_label": "Figure 6.", "figure_caption": "Left: refractive indices of aggregate particles, obtained using the Garnett EMT, as functions of wavelength for four different temperature regimes in which all materials are present (black), water ice has evaporated (red), organics have evaporated (green) and troilite has evaporated (blue). The temperatures at which these transitions occur are shown in Table&nbsp;1. Right: ratio of solid&sol;porous particle EMT refractive indices in the four temperature regions, for a porosity of 90&percnt;. For porosities in this range, these refractive indices could simply be used in our basic Equations&nbsp;(8) and ((9) or&nbsp;(12)), along with Equation&nbsp;(13) as constrained by Equations&nbsp;(15)&ndash;(17). These results would be used in our model to calculate particle opacities at temperatures where one or more of the five basic constituents has evaporated or decomposed (this is, of course, implicit in calculation of Rosseland mean opacities as a function of temperature, but the monochromatic opacities shown here are for a temperature where all candidate solids are condensed). Tabulated values available from the authors and will be posted online.\\n(A color version and supplemental data of this figure are available in the <inline-supplementary-material xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" content-type=\\"Supplemental data\\" xlink:title=\\"Figure 6\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs489879f6.tar.gz\\">online</inline-supplementary-material> journal.)"}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489879f7", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489879f7", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/21/apjs489879f7_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489879f7", "figure_label": "Figure 7.", "figure_caption": "Comparison of the wavelength-dependent mean extinction efficiency <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $Q^{\\\\prime }_e(\\\\lambda)$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs489879ieqn11.gif\\"/></inline-formula>, weighted and summed over the Pollack et&nbsp;al. (1994) particle size distribution, for two particle structure assumptions. The heterogeneous mixture in which each composition <italic>j</italic> is treated as a separate pure material with the same size distribution, and the various <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $Q^{\\\\prime }_{ej}(\\\\lambda)$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs489879ieqn12.gif\\"/></inline-formula> then combined using their appropriate abundances, is shown in black for our model and green for Mie theory. Also shown (red) is the Garnett EMT treatment of the same size distribution, but with each particle an identical aggregate of the five materials, along with (blue) the linear mixture &ldquo;approximation&rdquo; to EMT. Note how badly the linear approximation performs, as also discussed in Appendix&nbsp;C. On the other hand, for these small particles, the heterogeneous mixture and the Garnett EMT results are very similar."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489879f8", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489879f8", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/21/apjs489879f8_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489879f8", "figure_label": "Figure 8.", "figure_caption": "Monochromatic opacity in pure absorption (e.g., using only <italic>Q<sub>a</sub></italic>), such as would be relevant to interpreting mm&ndash;cm wavelength observations of disk fluxes. Two powerlaw distributions are shown, all of the form <italic>n</italic>(<italic>r</italic>) &equals; <italic>n<sub>o</sub>r</italic><sup>&minus;<italic>s</italic></sup>, where <italic>n</italic>(<italic>r</italic>) is a particle number density per unit particle radius, with three different values of <italic>r</italic><sub>max</sub>. The particles are aggregates of mixed cosmic composition at 100&nbsp;K. Left: solid particles (porosity = 0); right: porous particles (porosity = 0.9)."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489879f9", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489879f9", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/21/apjs489879f9_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489879f9", "figure_label": "Figure 9.", "figure_caption": "Monochromatic opacity, comparing Mie calculations for solid particles (dashed lines) with our model for porous particles (solid lines). Two powerlaw distributions are shown: <italic>s</italic> = 2.0 (heavy lines) and <italic>s</italic> = 3.1 (light lines), and the upper size is varied from 1&nbsp;mm to 100&nbsp;cm (the 10 and 100&nbsp;cm size results are not shown for the Mie case because the mm-wavelength slopes would be too flat and the calculations are onerous). The widely used opacity law of Beckwith et&nbsp;al. (1990) is the dashed line labeled B90. In principle, meter-size, very porous aggregates could be compatible with the <italic>slope</italic> of the mm-wavelength opacities; however as discussed in the text we believe that solid, or nearly solid, cm-size particles are more realistic."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489879f10", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489879f10", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/21/apjs489879f10_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489879f10", "figure_label": "Figure 10.", "figure_caption": "Rosseland mean opacities for various particle sizes and porosities, all calculated using our approach. Green: heterogeneous ISM distribution of Pollack et&nbsp;al. (1994); black curves: solid aggregate particles of no porosity with the same mass; solid: 10&thinsp;&mu;m radius monodispersion; dashed: 100&thinsp;&mu;m radius monodispersion; dotted: 1000&thinsp;&mu;m radius monodispersion (multiplied by 10). Also shown are red: 100&thinsp;&mu;m radius monodispersion with the same mass but porosity of 70&percnt;; blue: 100&thinsp;&mu;m radius monodispersion with the same mass but porosity of 90&percnt; (discussed in Section&nbsp;5.2)."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489879f11", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489879f11", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/21/apjs489879f11_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489879f11", "figure_label": "Figure 11.", "figure_caption": "Rosseland mean opacities for the same powerlaw size and porosity distributions as used in Figure&nbsp;8. Both linear and logarithmic forms are presented for the same results. Green: heterogeneous ISM distribution of Pollack et&nbsp;al. (1994); black curves: solid aggregate particles of no porosity with the same mass and powerlaw size distributions of differential slope 3.1; solid: 1&ndash;10&thinsp;&mu;m radius; dashed: 1&ndash;100&thinsp;&mu;m radius; dotted: 1&thinsp;&mu;m&ndash;1&nbsp;mm radius; dot-dash: 1&thinsp;&mu;m&ndash;1&nbsp;cm radius (shown are red: 1&thinsp;&mu;m&ndash;1&nbsp;cm radius with porosity of 90&percnt;."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs489879f12", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs489879f12", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/21/apjs489879f12_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs489879f12", "figure_label": "Figure 12.", "figure_caption": "Plots of the real (left) and imaginary (right) components of average refractive index of a material of density &rho; as a function of the density ratio <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $\\\\rho /\\\\overline{\\\\rho }$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs489879ieqn25.gif\\"/></inline-formula>. Curves marked (a) correspond to pure ice. Curves (b and c) correspond to two component mixtures of ice and rock (b) and ice and iron (c). Curve (d) corresponds to a three component mixtures of ice, rock, and troilite, while curve (e) contains these three as well as organics and iron. Note that the linear and Garnett correlate very poorly for mixtures that contain even small mixing ratios of elements with very high refractive indices. This message is also conveyed by Figure&nbsp;7 and the associated discussion."}]	2015-03-19 11:49:39.773894
