mperature at mean density (<italic>T</italic><sub>0</sub>) for gas elements at each of <italic>z</italic> &equals; 4.5, 5.0, and 5.5 as a function of their reionization redshift. Bottom panel: this is similar to the top panel, except it shows the slope of the temperature&ndash;density relation (&gamma; &minus; 1) rather than <italic>T</italic><sub>0</sub>. Note that although we assume that gas elements with a given reionization redshift all land on a well-defined temperature&ndash;density relation, this will not generally be a good description once we account for the spread in reionization redshift across the universe."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj495884f3", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj495884f3", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/788/2/175/apj495884f3_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj495884f3", "figure_label": "Figure 3.", "figure_caption": "Reionization redshifts and temperatures at <italic>z</italic> &equals; 5.5 in the low-<italic>z</italic> reionization model. Top panel: the reionization redshifts for a narrow slice (0.25&nbsp;Mpc <italic>h</italic><sup>&minus;1</sup> thick) through the simulation. Each slice is 130&nbsp;Mpc <italic>h</italic><sup>&minus;1</sup> on a side. The red regions indicate locations with the highest reionization redshifts across the simulation slice, while the dark regions are the last to be reionized. Bottom panel: the temperature of the same slice as in the top panel. The red areas in this panel show the hottest locations in the slice, and correspond to the dark regions in the top panel that are reionized late. The dark blue regions in the temperature slice, on the other hand, are the coolest regions that reionized first. The color scales are chosen so that 99&percnt; of simulation cells in the slice shown here have redshifts and temperatures falling between the minimum and maximum values on the color bar."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj495884f4", "highres": "http://ww