m/aasie/images/0004-637X/788/2/174/apj495733f2_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj495733f2", "figure_label": "Figure 2.", "figure_caption": "Top: the spectral index image (rotated by 90&deg;). Bottom: the one-dimensional spectral index profile, drawn along the brightness ridge of the source J2345&minus;0449 between 325&nbsp;MHz (GMRT) and 1400&nbsp;MHz (VLA&sol;NVSS) frequency is shown. In the spectral index map, all pixels with a flux density below 2&nbsp;mJy&nbsp;beam<sup>&minus;1</sup> at 1400&nbsp;MHz (&sim;4&sigma;) and 15&nbsp;mJy&nbsp;beam<sup>&minus;1</sup> at 325&nbsp;MHz (&sim;5&sigma;) have been blanked to prevent spurious structures from appearing in the map. An outline of the optical galaxy is shown by a blue ellipse, and the yellow circle within a box shows the 45&Prime;&nbsp;&times; 45&Prime; beam. The spectral index &alpha; is defined as flux density (<italic>S</italic><sub>&nu;</sub>) &prop; frequency(&nu;)<sup>&minus;&alpha;</sup>. The typical error (1&sigma;) in the estimation of spectral index is shown at the top right corner of the one-dimensional profile figure. The positions of the radio core, the inner double lobes, and the outer lobes of the radio source have been marked. Note a sharp increase in the spectral index between the inner and outer radio lobe pairs."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj495733f3", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj495733f3", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/788/2/174/apj495733f3_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj495733f3", "figure_label": "Figure 3.", "figure_caption": "Large-scale galactic environment around J2345&minus;0449. The color image, taken from the Sloan Digital Sky Survey-III, shows a field of view of &sim;1&thinsp;Mpc &times; 1&thinsp;Mpc centered on J2345&minus;0449. The three nearest and brightest galaxies are marked in the descending order of their brightness in <italic>r</italic>-band: galaxy no. 1 (<italic>m<sub>r</sub></italic> &equals; 16.50, <italic>z</italic><sub>ph</sub> &equals; 0.0697), galaxy no. 2 (<italic>m<sub>r</sub></italic> &equals; 16.87, <italic>z</italic><sub>ph</sub> &equals; 0.0615), and galaxy no. 3 (<italic>m<sub>r</sub></italic> &equals; 17.07, <italic>z</italic><sub>ph</sub> &equals; 0.0798). Here <italic>z</italic><sub>ph</sub> denotes the photometric redshift obtained from SDSS. The magnitude of spiral galaxy J2345&minus;0449 is <italic>m<sub>r</sub></italic> &equals; 14.40 in <italic>r</italic> with spectroscopic redshift 0.07556. All magnitudes are galactic extinction corrected and taken from SDSS."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj495733f4", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj495733f4", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/788/2/174/apj495733f4_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj495733f4", "figure_label": "Figure 4.", "figure_caption": "Major axis spectrum taken with IFOSC on IUCAA 2&nbsp;m telescope, centered on the nucleus. The absorption lines are marked by blue dot-dashed lines, and the expected positions of the emission lines are marked with magenta dashed lines. The red edge of the spectrum is contaminated by telluric features. A telluric reference spectrum is shown in green at the bottom."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj495733f5", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj495733f5", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/788/2/174/apj495733f5_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj495733f5", "figure_label": "Figure 5.", "figure_caption": "Top panels: two-dimensional images showing the long-slit spectrum near the H&alpha; and [N&thinsp;<sc>ii</sc>] emission lines of galaxy J2345&minus;0449. Locations of different sub-apertures (numbers 1&ndash;15) used to derive the rotation curve of the galaxy are marked in the zoomed right-hand side image. The wavelength direction is horizontal, increasing to the right, and the spatial direction is vertical. A sharply rising flat rotation curve is clearly evident in the shape of both H&alpha; and [N&thinsp;<sc>ii</sc>] lines marked here. Bottom: panels: one-dimensional spectra extracted at different sub-apertures as indicated in the above figure. Gaussian fits to H&alpha; and [N&thinsp;<sc>ii</sc>] lines are shown for the blueshifted and redshifted wings of the spectra. The flux scale is arbitrary. No significant H&alpha; emission was detected in the central apertures numbered 7 and 8. The parameters derived from the Gaussian fits are used to obtain the rotation curve (Figure 6) and the radial dependence of star formation rate and metallicity (Figure 7)."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj495733f6", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj495733f6", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/788/2/174/apj495733f6_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj495733f6", "figure_label": "Figure 6.", "figure_caption": "Optical image and the rotation curve of spiral galaxy J2345&minus;0449. Top: a color composite from combining the deep optical images taken with the <italic>MegaCam</italic> on the Canada&ndash;France&ndash;Hawaii Telescope (CFHT) in subarcsecond seeing. Bottom: the rotation curve of the galaxy (red dashed curve) derived from the kinematics of the Balmer H&alpha; line in the long-slit spectrum taken along the major axis (red data points) and minor axis (blue data points). The rotational velocity is shown without the sin(<italic>i</italic>) correction for inclination. The major axis data shows a clear rotation signature, while no such rotation is evident across the minor axis, which is clear evidence that the emission originates in a tilted rotating disk. For reference the scale length of the stellar bulge component (<italic>R</italic><sub>e</sub>) and the radii containing 50&percnt; (<italic>R</italic><sub>50</sub>) and 90&percnt; (<italic>R</italic><sub>90</sub>) of the total optical light in the <italic>r</italic> band is shown by red and blue dot-dashed vertical lines."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj495733f7", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj495733f7", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/788/2/174/apj495733f7_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj495733f7", "figure_label": "Figure 7.", "figure_caption": "Surface star formation rate (SFR) computed at different radial positions along the major axis of the galaxy is shown in the top panel. The circles and squares are the values computed using the prescription given by Argence &amp; Lamareille (2009) and Kennicut (1992), respectively. Here we have not applied any correction for dust extinction. The derived oxygen abundances are shown in the bottom panel. The red horizontal dashed line marks the solar oxygen abundance."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj495733f8", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj495733f8", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/788/2/174/apj495733f8_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj495733f8", "figure_label": "Figure 8.", "figure_caption": "One-dimensional surface brightness profile comparison. The black squares are observational data points obtained from the CFHT image in the <italic>g</italic> band (left panel) and the <italic>r</italic>-band (right panel). Red and blue lines are the model profiles for the bulge and disk components, respectively. The black line shows the combined profile by adding the bulge and disk parts. The model profiles were obtained from a point-spread function (PSF) convolved image generated by the GALFIT software, as described in the main text."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj495733f9", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj495733f9", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/788/2/174/apj495733f9_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj495733f9", "figure_label": "Figure 9.", "figure_caption": "These figure panels show the comparison of structural and photometric properties of the bulge in the present spiral galaxy J2345&minus;0449 with bulges in other galaxies (both classical and pseudobulges) as shown in Fisher &amp; Drory (2008). Here <italic>n<sub>b</sub></italic>, <italic>M<sub>V</sub></italic>, <italic>r<sub>e</sub></italic>, and &mu;<sub><italic>e</italic></sub> denote the S&eacute;rsic index, absolute <italic>V</italic> magnitude, scale radius, and average surface brightness within <italic>r<sub>e</sub></italic> of the bulge, respectively. The dashed line in the first figure panel separates the classical bulges (<italic>n<sub>b</sub></italic> &gt; 2) from pseudobulges (<italic>n<sub>b</sub></italic> &lt; 2). The &epsi;<sub><italic>b</italic></sub> and &epsi;<sub><italic>d</italic></sub> are the ellipticity of bulge and disk components, and B&sol;T is the bulge-to-total light ratio. T-type is the morphological type of the galaxy (see the main text). Blue crosses and red open circles represent the pseudobulges and classical bulges, respectively, in spirals, and the filled red dot represents the present galaxy J2345&minus;0449, while black filled points correspond to the ellipticals. J2345&minus;0449 clearly belongs to the pseudobulge category as seen on most of these plots. We show two red dots in last figure panel, one for T-type = 1 (Sa) and other for T-type = 2 (Sab). This is to take care of the uncertainty in the visual T-type of the present galaxy."}]	2015-03-19 11:50:11.360362
