shows the error after the first iteration. The remaining large-scale errors can be represented on a coarser grid. This observation leads to the multi-level algorithm."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490040f3", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490040f3", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/24/apjs490040f3_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490040f3", "figure_label": "Figure 3.", "figure_caption": "Effect of filters in harmonic domain for the top five levels. For each level <italic>H</italic>, starting from the original system of Equation&nbsp;(4) at the top, we plot the transfer filter <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $f^H_{h,\\\\ell }$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn34.gif\\"/></inline-formula> (dotted blue), the filtered prior <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $(\\\\tilde{f}^H_\\\\ell)^2/C_\\\\ell$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn35.gif\\"/></inline-formula> (solid black), and an approximation to the diagonal of the inverse-noise term (dashed red). Functions are normalized to an arbitrary scale (see Figure&nbsp;4 for the absolute scale). Note how the prior term on the pixel levels looks superficially similar to wavelets&sol;needlets in harmonic domain (Scodeller et&nbsp;al. 2011, and references therein). The real-space transform is also similar to wavelets&sol;needlets (not plotted)."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490040f4", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490040f4", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/24/apjs490040f4_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490040f4", "figure_label": "Figure 4.", "figure_caption": "Same as Figure&nbsp;3, but all levels plotted together with a logarithmic scale and with absolute normalization. We plot the filtered prior <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $(\\\\tilde{f}^H_\\\\ell)^2/C_\\\\ell$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn36.gif\\"/></inline-formula> (solid), and the diagonal of the inverse-noise term for 26&thinsp;&mu;K constant rms and no mask (dashed). This noise level corresponds to the average of the rms map of the 143&nbsp;GHz Planck band. The levels are: the original system (black), <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $N^h_{{\\\\rm side}}=1024$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn37.gif\\"/></inline-formula> (red), <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $N^h_{{\\\\rm side}}=512$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn38.gif\\"/></inline-formula> (blue), <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $N^h_{{\\\\rm side}}=256$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn39.gif\\"/></inline-formula> (orange), and <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $N^h_{{\\\\rm side}}=128$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn40.gif\\"/></inline-formula> (green). Note the effect of the filters on the signal-to-noise ratio; harmonic scales go from being data-dominated to noise-dominated at the point where the solid and dashed lines intersect."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490040f5", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490040f5", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/24/apjs490040f5_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490040f5", "figure_label": "Figure 5.", "figure_caption": "Multi-level CR solver. The matrices involved are defined in the main text. In place of the simple iteration scheme of CR-Solve, one can use CR-Cycle as a preconditioner within another solver, such as CG. By varying the <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $n_{\\\\rm rec}^h$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn48.gif\\"/></inline-formula> parameter, a variety of solver cycles can be constructed, such as a V-cycle (<inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $n_{\\\\rm rec}^h=1$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn49.gif\\"/></inline-formula>) or W-cycle (<inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $n_{\\\\rm rec}^h=2$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn50.gif\\"/></inline-formula>). Note that, for simplicity, the top-level diagonal error correction is omitted; see the main text."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490040f6", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490040f6", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/24/apjs490040f6_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490040f6", "figure_label": "Figure 6.", "figure_caption": "Effect of a poor choice of filter <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $\\\\tilde{f}_\\\\ell ^h$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn75.gif\\"/></inline-formula>. Each panel shows the couplings between a single pixel and its neighboring region, corresponding to a row&sol;column of <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $\\\\widehat{\\\\mathbf {A}}_h$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn76.gif\\"/></inline-formula>. In this case we used a low-pass filter based on modifying a standard needlet (Scodeller et&nbsp;al. 2011, and references therein). While the harmonic properties of this filter were very attractive, the tails do not decay quickly enough in real space. The resulting strong, long-range couplings are fatal to our algorithm."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490040f7", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490040f7", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/24/apjs490040f7_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490040f7", "figure_label": "Figure 7.", "figure_caption": "Effect of the mask on <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $\\\\widehat{\\\\mathbf {A}}_h$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn77.gif\\"/></inline-formula>. Each panel shows the coupling strength in absolute value in the <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $\\\\widehat{\\\\mathbf {A}}_h$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn78.gif\\"/></inline-formula> operator, between a sample point at (&theta;, &phi;) (plotted at the origin), and another sample point <italic>n</italic> pixels away at (&theta;, &phi; &plus; <italic>n</italic>&Delta;), where &Delta; is the angular size of one pixel. The couplings of <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $\\\\widehat{\\\\mathbf {A}}_h$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn79.gif\\"/></inline-formula> (black) are a sum of the prior term <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $\\\\widehat{\\\\mathbf {D}}_h$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn80.gif\\"/></inline-formula> (dotted blue) and the inverse-noise term <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $\\\\widehat{\\\\mathbf {B}}_h^T \\\\mathbf {N}^{-1} \\\\widehat{\\\\mathbf {B}}_h$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn81.gif\\"/></inline-formula> (dashed red). For each panel, we vary the position of (&theta;, &phi;) relative to the mask (gray band), so that the origin is in each case a value on the diagonal of <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $\\\\widehat{\\\\mathbf {A}}_h$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn82.gif\\"/></inline-formula>. Displayed here is our <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $N^h_{{\\\\rm side}}=32$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn83.gif\\"/></inline-formula> level in the case of 1.9&nbsp;&mu;K constant rms noise (the minimum rms level of the Planck 143&nbsp;GHz band). The filter <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $\\\\tilde{f}_\\\\ell$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn84.gif\\"/></inline-formula> is a product of all the inter-level filters <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $f^h_{H,\\\\ell }$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn85.gif\\"/></inline-formula> (as described in the text), but corresponds roughly to a Gaussian with FWHM of 2 pixels divided by the pixel window <italic>p</italic><sub>&ell;</sub>. The &ldquo;floor&rdquo; at 10<sup>&minus;1</sup> is caused by the non-Gaussian features of the instrumental beam, <italic>b</italic><sub>&ell;</sub>. For comparison, a perfect Gaussian instrumental beam is used in Figure&nbsp;9."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490040f8", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490040f8", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/24/apjs490040f8_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490040f8", "figure_label": "Figure 8.", "figure_caption": "Effect of resolution on <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $\\\\widehat{\\\\mathbf {A}}_h$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn91.gif\\"/></inline-formula>. See Figure&nbsp;7 for legend and experimental setup. In this figure, we also show the effect of the filter <italic>q</italic><sub>&ell;</sub> of Equation&nbsp;(24), with &lambda; appropriately tuned for the resolution in each case. As the resolution is increased, the signal-to-noise ratio decreases, making the influence of the edge of the mask less important."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490040f9", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490040f9", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/24/apjs490040f9_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490040f9", "figure_label": "Figure 9.", "figure_caption": "Effect of the band-limit <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA ${\\\\ell ^h_{\\\\rm max}}$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn96.gif\\"/></inline-formula> on <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $\\\\widehat{\\\\mathbf {A}}_h$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn97.gif\\"/></inline-formula>. See Figure&nbsp;7 for legend and experimental setup. The settings for each panel are the same except for varying <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA ${\\\\ell ^h_{\\\\rm max}}$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn98.gif\\"/></inline-formula>. Here, the product <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $\\\\tilde{f}_\\\\ell ^h b_\\\\ell p_\\\\ell$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490040ieqn99.gif\\"/></inline-formula> is a pure Gaussian with FWHM of 2&nbsp;pixels. Since the instrumental beam is in this case taken to be a perfect Gaussian, there is also no &ldquo;floor&rdquo; at 10<sup>&minus;1</sup> (compare with Figure&nbsp;7 for the effect of a non-Gaussian beam)."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490040f10", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490040f10", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/210/2/24/apjs490040f10_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490040f10", "figure_label": "Figure 10.", "figure_caption": "Structure of the block sparse matrices used in the error smoothers. Top panel: the sparsity pattern when every tile is coupled to its eight neighboring tiles. In this case, the pattern of tiles is an <italic>N</italic><sub>side</sub