1153	2014ApJ...792...17S	10.1088/0004-637X/792/1/17	IOP	f	[{"images": [{"image_id": "apj497763f1", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj497763f1", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/792/1/17/apj497763f1_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj497763f1", "figure_label": "Figure 1.", "figure_caption": "Characteristic examples of exoplanet-to-star contrasts (i.e., flux ratios) as a function of wavelength, showing that (1) gas-giant exoplanets can be detected with lower contrasts in the mid-infrared (3&ndash;5&nbsp;&mu;m) than in the near-infrared (1&ndash;2&nbsp;&mu;m), and (2) this difference increases at lower temperatures. While the planets that have been directly imaged to date (&beta; Pic b and HR&nbsp;8799 c, d, and e on this plot) are relatively warm (1600&nbsp;K and 1000&nbsp;K, respectively), it is likely that the majority of self-luminous exoplanets are much cooler. Planets that formed by core-accretion (approximated by the &ldquo;cold-start&rdquo; models; Fortney et al. 2008) are never hotter than &sim;700&nbsp;K. Planets around average-aged stars (5&nbsp;Gyr) are never hotter than &sim;400&nbsp;K, regardless of formation history. Jupiter, which may be a ubiquitous outcome of planet formation, is only &sim;130&nbsp;K. (Models from Madhusudhan et al. 2011; Burrows et al. 2003)."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj497763f2", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj497763f2", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/792/1/17/apj497763f2_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj497763f2", "figure_label": "Figure 2.", "figure_caption": "LBTI&sol;LMIRCam images of the HR&nbsp;8799 planetary system in six narrow-band filters. Each wavelength was observed for seven minutes with the incoherently combined 2 &times; 8.4&nbsp;m LBT aperture. HR&nbsp;8799 c and d are visible in all six filters. HR&nbsp;8799 b is visible in four of the six filters, although it is low S&sol;N, given the short integration times. HR&nbsp;8799 e is also detectable at low S&sol;N in the longest wavelength filters, given its known position. The planet positions are circled in the lower right panel. North is up and East is left. The images are each 3&farcs;5 across."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj497763f3", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj497763f3", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/792/1/17/apj497763f3_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj497763f3", "figure_label": "Figure 3.", "figure_caption": "MagAO&sol;Clio2 images of the 2M1207 system. The binary is clearly resolved despite being 38&Prime; off-axis from its faint (<italic>R</italic> &sim; 14.2) AO guide-star. The slight elongation of 2M1207 A is from the anisoplanatism of the off-axis AO reference star. 2M1207 b appears to be circular because of the image stretch, which just shows its diffraction-limited core (FWHM = 0&farcs;1). North is up and East is left. The field-of-view shown here is 2 &times; 2&farcs;5."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj497763f4", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj497763f4", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/792/1/17/apj497763f4_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj497763f4", "figure_label": "Figure 4.", "figure_caption": "Color&ndash;magnitude diagrams showing the positions of directly imaged extrasolar planets with respect to field brown dwarfs. In the left panel, the HR&nbsp;8799 planets and 2M1207 b appear to be a continuation of the L-dwarf sequence, implying that the planets have clouds at fainter absolute <italic>H</italic>-band magnitudes than the field brown dwarfs. The recently discovered GJ 504 b also appears below the L-dwarf sequence, although other near-infrared colors place it with the field T dwarfs. In the middle panel, the directly imaged planets are systematically bluer than the field brown dwarfs, suggesting that their 3.3&nbsp;&mu;m methane absorption feature is somewhat diminished through some combination of clouds and non-equilibrium CO &harr; CH<sub>4</sub> chemistry. The right panel shows the directly imaged planets as relatively consistent with the field brown dwarfs, although with large error bars. For all three plots, error bars in the upper right corner represent the maximum error bar for the brown dwarf sample."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj497763f5", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj497763f5", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/792/1/17/apj497763f5_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj497763f5", "figure_label": "Figure 5.", "figure_caption": "Absolute photometry for HR&nbsp;8799 cd and 2M1207 b compared to thick-cloud atmosphere models. The photometric data are shown as red error bars, the model spectra are shown as blue curves, and the model photometric predictions are shown as blue horizontal lines spanning the filter half-maximums. The thick-cloud models are adopted from Madhusudhan et al. (2011) for HR&nbsp;8799 cd and Skemer et al. (2011) for 2M1207 b, using the grid from Madhusudhan et al. (2011). Two cloud parameterizations are used: A-type, which are the thickest clouds in Madhusudhan et al. (2011) and AE-type, which are slightly thinner. For all three objects, the broad-band photometry (left side of the figure) is generally well-fit by the models, except for the [3.3&nbsp;&mu;m] filter. Our new narrow-band 3&ndash;4&nbsp;&mu;m photometry (right side of the figure) is consistent with broader-band photometry at similar wavelengths, although systematically brighter within errors."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj497763f6", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj497763f6", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/792/1/17/apj497763f6_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj497763f6", "figure_label": "Figure 6.", "figure_caption": "Same as Figure 5, but with models that include non-equilibrium CO &harr; CH<sub>4</sub> chemistry or parameterized CO&sol;CH<sub>4</sub> opacity. The <italic>Burrows</italic> models are from Skemer et al. (2012) and have similar clouds properties as Figure 5 but with diminished CH<sub>4</sub> and enhanced CO opacity. The <italic>Barman</italic> model, which is from Barman et al. (2011b), also employs thick clouds and uses chemical reaction rates to self-consistently calculate CH<sub>4</sub> and CO mixing ratios assuming a vertical diffusion coefficient of <italic>K<sub>zz</sub></italic> &equals; 10<sup>8</sup>&thinsp;cm<sup>2</sup>&thinsp;s<sup>&minus;1</sup>. The HR&nbsp;8799 planets are not well-fit by the <italic>Burrows</italic> models, which predict a sharp edge to the methane absorption feature, even with suppressed methane opacity. Our new narrow-band 3&ndash;4&nbsp;&mu;m photometry suggest a smoother slope. Note that analogous models from Barman et al. (2011a) and Galicher et al. (2011) predict qualitatively similar behavior (when considering models that have radii consistent with evolutionary tracks). However, the <italic>Barman</italic> model fits 2M1207 b quite well, including our new [3.3&nbsp;&mu;m] photometry. Combined with Barman et al. (2011b)&apos;s fit of the 2M1207 b near-infrared spectrum, it appears that thick clouds and non-equilibrium chemistry can explain all of the existing data for 2M1207 b."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj497763f7", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj497763f7", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/792/1/17/apj497763f7_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj497763f7", "figure_label": "Figure 7.", "figure_caption": "Same as Figure 5, but with models that linearly combine two different thick-cloud atmosphere models to represent non-isotropic emission through regions with different temperatures and different cloud properties. The models are from Skemer et al. (2012) using the grid from Madhusudhan et al. (2011). The HR&nbsp;8799 planets are reasonably well-fit by the data. However, the modeling approach of linearly combining two-atmosphere models is not entirely self-consistent, so additional modeling (Section 4.4) is needed to study patchy cloud models."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj497763f8", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj497763f8", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/792/1/17/apj497763f8_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj497763f8", "figure_label": "Figure 8.", "figure_caption": "Same as Figure 5, but with self-consistent patchy clouds calculated using the formalism of Marley et al. (2010). The thick-cloud models use <italic>f</italic><sub>sed</sub>&nbsp;=&nbsp;0.25 (Ackerman &amp; Marley 2001), which are very thick clouds. The models with patches of thin clouds also use <italic>f</italic><sub>sed</sub>&nbsp;=&nbsp;0.25, but with 30&percnt; of the surface having 10&percnt; of the normal cloud opacity. In the third set of models, 10&percnt; of the surface has no cloud opacity. The HR&nbsp;8799 planets are not well-fit by any of the models. The thick-cloud models and models with thin cloud patches both wash out the near-infrared SED where spectra of HR&nbsp;8799 b, c, and 2M1207 b show strong water absorption bands (Barman et al. 2011a; Konopacky et al. 2013; Patience et al. 2010). The models with cloud-free holes still have too much methane absorption from &sim;3.1 to 3.6&nbsp;&mu;m."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj497763f9", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj497763f9", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/792/1/17/apj497763f9_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj497763f9", "figure_label": "Figure 9.", "figure_caption": "Same as Figure 5, but with self-consistent patchy clouds calculated using the formalism of Marley et al. (2010) combined with non-equilibrium chemistry as described in Saumon et al. (2006). The non-equilibrium models use a diffusion coefficient of <italic>K<sub>zz</sub></italic> &equals; 10<sup>6</sup>&thinsp;cm<sup>2</sup>&thinsp;s<sup>&minus;1</sup>. Both of the HR&nbsp;8799 planets are reasonably well-fit by the patchy-cloud/non-equilibrium chemistry model, although the model clearly overpredicts the <italic>M</italic>-band (4.7&nbsp;&mu;m) flux of HR&nbsp;8799&thinsp;c. These models are a heuristic demonstration of the type of processes that are likely shaping the spectra of these directly imaged planets, although clearly more detailed model fits are required to find the best fitting parameters."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj497763f10", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj497763f10", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/792/1/17/apj497763f10_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj497763f10", "figure_label": "Figure 10.", "figure_caption": "Filter profiles for the seven filters used in this work and a model telluric profile for 1.0 airmasses and 4.3&nbsp;mm precipitable water vapor (Gemini Cerro Pachon model from <ext-link ext-link-type=\\"url\\" xlink:href=\\"http://www.gemini.edu/sciops/telescopes-and-sites/observing-condition-constraints/ir-transmission-spectra\\">http://www.gemini.edu/sciops/telescopes-and-sites/observing-condition-constraints/ir-transmission-spectra</ext-link>). The telluric transmission, which is variable, can significantly affect the raw filter properties, which are listed in Table 4. Also shown is an opacity plot for methane (linear scaling), which demonstrates the utility of the filters for measuring methane absorption in cool atmospheres."}]	2015-03-19 11:52:24.890701
