) lines. The solid lines (black) indicate the O5 sample, while the O3 sample is shown by the gray shaded regions. Arrows indicate the median stellar mass of each sample. The lower panels show the cumulative fraction of each sample, with gray dashed lines representing the O3 sample."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj497708f9", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj497708f9", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/792/1/16/apj497708f9_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj497708f9", "figure_label": "Figure 9.", "figure_caption": "Cumulative projected radial distributions of different types of galaxies as a function of virial radius. The projected distance is first normalized by the virial radius of each cluster or group and then combined. In clusters, K+A galaxies are centrally concentrated, even more than red sequence galaxies. Group K+A galaxies, on the other hand, are evenly distributed."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj497708f10", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apj497708f10", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0004-637X/792/1/16/apj497708f10_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apj497708f10", "figure_label": "Figure 10.", "figure_caption": "Cumulative projected radial distributions of K+A and 24&thinsp;&mu;m detected galaxies in clusters and groups. 24&thinsp;&mu;m undetected K+A galaxies, 24&thinsp;&mu;m detected K+A galaxies, and 24&thinsp;&mu;m detected non-K+A galaxies are represented by solid lines (red), dashed lines (magenta), and dash-dotted (blue) lines, respectively. In clusters, K+A galaxies share a similar projected radial distribution, regardless of whether they are detected at 24&thinsp;&mu;m or not. On the other hand, the distribution of 24&thinsp;&mu;m detected K+A galaxies is distinct from other 24&thinsp;&mu;m detected galaxies. In groups, the three subsamples show moderate differences."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apj497708f11", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.