mbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/215/1/9/apjs502042f20_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs502042f20", "figure_label": "Figure 20.", "figure_caption": "Root mean square scatter in the positive and negative directions (thick) and median (thin) of artificial star tests as a function of (and relative to) input magnitude in all six bands at five different stellar densities (number of stars with 18.5 &lt; F160W &lt; 19.5 per arcsec<sup>2</sup>). Both the bias and the rms scatter are very small at the bright end. In the UV bands, the errors at the faint end only reach &sim;0.2&nbsp;mag, and the bias is faintward. In redder bands with low crowding, the bias is near 0, and the errors are &sim;0.2&nbsp;mag at the faint end. In crowded regions, the bias and the errors can reach &gt;0.5&nbsp;mag, and the bias is brightward."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs502042f21", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs502042f21", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/215/1/9/apjs502042f21_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs502042f21", "figure_label": "Figure 21.", "figure_caption": "rms scatter in the positive and negative directions (thick) and median (thin) in color as a function of magnitude and stellar density (number of stars with 18.5 &lt; F160W &lt; 19.5 per arcsec<sup>2</sup>). Color scatter increases substantially with stellar density, but the bias remains low, except right at the magnitude limit, where the bias can be large and relatively unpredictable."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs502042f22", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs502042f22", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/215/1/9/apjs502042f22_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs502042f22", "figure_label": "Figure 22.", "figure_caption": "Ratio of the rms from artificial star tests to the DOLPHOT-reported uncertainty as a function of magnitude for a range of stellar densities. Each panel gives the results for a different filter, as labeled, and each line color represents a different stellar density (number of stars with 18.5 &lt; F160W &lt; 19.5 per arcsec<sup>2</sup>), as labeled."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs502042f23", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs502042f23", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/215/1/9/apjs502042f23_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs502042f23", "figure_label": "Figure 23.", "figure_caption": "Completeness as a function of stellar density (number of stars with 18.5 &lt; F160W&lt; 19.5 per arcsec<sup>2</sup>) in the survey. There is a clear trend that the red bands are crowding-limited over much of the survey, while the UV bands are not."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs502042f24", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs502042f24", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/215/1/9/apjs502042f24_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs502042f24", "figure_label": "Figure 24.", "figure_caption": "Systematic magnitude and color variations for the same stars measured on different parts of the ACS&sol;WFC camera in F475W (top left), F814W (top middle), and F475W &minus; F814W (top right) from outside of the bulge, and on different parts of WFC3&sol;IR in F110W (bottom left), F160W (bottom middle), and F110W &minus; F160W (bottom right) from the overlap between Bricks 9 and 11. The systematic errors as a function of brightness are &sim; &plusmn;0.02&ndash;0.05 (see Table 9)."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs502042f25", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs502042f25", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/215/1/9/apjs502042f25_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs502042f25", "figure_label": "Figure 25.", "figure_caption": "Median sharpness values for the all stars outside of the bulge as a function of position on the ACS&sol;WFC camera in F475W (top left) and F814W (top right), and as 