 rates shown by the dashed lines indicate a net heating below <italic>T</italic> &sim; 10<sup>4.5</sup>, where the rapid change in rate is evident (the curve is an absolute value so it can be shown on a log plot). The red curve is the tabulated cooling function of Sarazin &amp; White (1987), which assumes a fully ionized gas with metallicity of 0.5&thinsp;<italic>Z</italic><sub>&sun;</sub>."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f4", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f4", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f4_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f4", "figure_label": "Figure 4.", "figure_caption": "Density distribution of the classic Sod Shock Tube for three different solvers (from left to right column) and with (bottom row) and without (top row) AMR. In each case 100 zones are used on the root level and the results are shown at <italic>t</italic> &equals; 0.25. All cells are plotted and color-coded by level with purple indicating level 0, green level 1 and red level 2 (at the time shown, only small region surrounding the contact discontinuity and the shock are refined). In each panel, we show the analytic solution as a solid line and the <italic>E</italic><sub>1</sub> error norm in the upper right."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f5", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f5", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f5_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f5", "figure_label": "Figure 5.", "figure_caption": "This plot shows, for each column, three snapshots at <italic>t</italic> &equals; 0.2, 0.3 and 0.8 of a linear wave as it propagates through the domain. A static refined region extends from <italic>x</italic> &equals; 0.25 to 0.75 and is shown in gray in each panel. The individual cells are also color-coded by level: blue indicates the root grid, and red is for the refined region. Each row shows the result for a different hydrodynamic solver (top is PPM, middle is ZEUS, and the bottom is MUSCL). The solid line shows the analytic solution for a linear, undamped wave. Note that we focus each panel on a small region of the entire domain to better show the wave itself."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f6", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f6", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f6_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f6", "figure_label": "Figure 6.", "figure_caption": "This plot shows, for each column, three snapshots at <italic>t</italic> &equals; 0.1, 0.15 and 0.35 of a <inline-formula><tex-math><?CDATA $\\\\mathcal {M}=2$?></tex-math><inline-graphic xmlns:xlink=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\\" xlink:href=\\"apjs490394ieqn71.gif\\"/></inline-formula> shock as it propagates through the grid with a static refined region extends from <italic>x</italic> &equals; 0.25 to 0.75 (shown in gray in each panel). Each row shows the result for a different solver (PPM&sol;ZEUS&sol;MUSCL from top to bottom). The solid line shows the analytic solution. Note that we focus each panel on a small region of the entire domain to better show the shock front."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f7", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f7", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f7_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f7", "figure_label": "Figure 7.", "figure_caption": "Density field at the final time in the Double Mach test. A Mach 10 shock is injected into the domain with a shock normal that is 30&deg; from the <italic>x</italic>-axis with a time-dependent +<italic>y</italic>-boundary condition that mimics a shock of infinite length. The solution is self-similar, with the jet and whorls at <italic>x</italic> &sime; 2.5&ndash;3.0 in this figure being very sensitive to numerical diffusion. Our results compare favorably to the higher-order images from Woodward &amp; Colella (1984a)."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f8", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f8", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f8_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f8", "figure_label": "Figure 8.", "figure_caption": "Density slices from the Sedov Blast test at <italic>t</italic> &equals; 0.07. Left: results using the PPM hydro scheme. Right: results using the ZEUS hydro method. Notably, the ZEUS shock front has progressed less far than in the PPM run. This is due to energy loss when conserving only internal, and not total, energy."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f9", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f9", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f9_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f9", "figure_label": "Figure 9.", "figure_caption": "Radial profiles for the Sedov Blast test at <italic>t</italic> &equals; 0.07. Clockwise from top-left shows density, velocity, internal energy, and pressure. The black solid line shows the analytic solution. The blue dashed line shows the simulation using the PPM method, and the red dot-dashed line using ZEUS. The ZEUS result substantially lags the true result due to total energy not being explicitly converged."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f10", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f10", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f10_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f10", "figure_label": "Figure 10.", "figure_caption": "Radial and tangential accelerations measured around a point source placed in a static AMR grid. The solid line shows the analytic radial profile."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f11", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f11", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f11_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f11", "figure_label": "Figure 11.", "figure_caption": "Test particle behavior in the Orbit problem, which is used to test the gravity solver and particle integration. An effectively massless test particle is set in circular orbit around a massive central particle, with the gravitational potential calculated on a three-dimensional, 32<sup>3</sup> grid, and evolved forward in time for 200 orbits. Left panel: path of the test particle in the orbital plane plotted for the duration of the simulation, with a zoomed box showing a small portion of the orbit to highlight deviations from perfect circularity. Right panel: total specific energy (kinetic plus potential) for the test particle for the duration of the simulation. The particle&apos;s mean energy (integrated over the length of the simulation) is represented by a horizontal dashed line, and +/&minus; one standard deviation by horizontal dotted lines. All quantities are in arbitrary units."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f12", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f12", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f12_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f12", "figure_label": "Figure 12.", "figure_caption": "Results of the self-similar spherical infall test. The panels show, as a function of the dimensionless radius &lambda;, the dimensionless density <italic>D</italic> (top left), velocity <italic>V</italic> (top right), pressure <italic>P</italic> (bottom left), and enclosed mass <italic>M</italic> (bottom right). In each case we show azimuthally averaged profiles from the simulation as circles and the analytic solution for &gamma; &equals; 5&sol;3 as solid lines."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f13", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f13", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f13_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f13", "figure_label": "Figure 13.", "figure_caption": "Zel&lsquo;Dovich Pancake test shown at <italic>z</italic> &equals; 0, initialized in a &Omega;<sub><italic>m</italic></sub> &equals; 1 universe at <italic>z</italic> &equals; 20 on a one-dimensional grid having 64 cells, and further refined by factors of four based on cell mass and the presence of shocks for up to two additional levels of mesh, having a maximum effective resolution of 1024 grid cells. The top, middle, and bottom rows show density, temperature, and velocity of the gas, respectively; all are a function of position in units of the box size. The central region (<italic>x</italic> &sime; 0.45&ndash;0.55) has been adaptively refined, as can be seen by the locations of grid points. Shocks and the central density peak are clearly resolved, with well-delineated jumps at the appropriate locations."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f14", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f14", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f14_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f14", "figure_label": "Figure 14.", "figure_caption": "Shock tube of Brio &amp; Wu (1988). Top panels show the result at <italic>t</italic> = 0.08 for the CT scheme (black line and points) and Dedner scheme (light gray line, entirely hidden behind black points) and reference solution, run at 10,000 zones. Bottom panels shows the difference between CT and Dedner."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f15", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f15", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f15_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f15", "figure_label": "Figure 15.", "figure_caption": "Density field from the Orszag&ndash;Tang vortex test, at <italic>t</italic> &equals; 0.48. Left: solution using constrained transport MHD. Right: solution using Dedner MHD. The initial conditions are uniform density, with a single rotating velocity structure and two circular magnetic structures. These initial conditions generate significant small-scale structure in both the CT and Dedner schemes, which have approximately equal effective resolution."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f16", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f16", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f16_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f16", "figure_label": "Figure 16.", "figure_caption": "Evolution of temperature vs. number density for a one-zone collapse test for gas at metallicities from 0 to 10<sup>&minus;2</sup>&thinsp;<italic>Z</italic><sub>&sun;</sub>. This test is based on the results of Omukai et al. (2005), and approximates the collapse of a self-gravitating, cooling gas cloud. This test problem uses Enzo&apos;s primordial chemistry network with tabulated metal cooling rates calculated with the <monospace>Cloudy</monospace> code, and compares favorably to the results of Omukai et al. (2005)."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f17", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f17", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f17_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f17", "figure_label": "Figure 17.", "figure_caption": "Results of the ionization balance test (Section 11.2.13) calculating the equilibrium ionization balance (left) and resulting cooling rate (right) of a primordial gas with no incident photo-ionizing radiation. Solid lines show the results of iterating the Enzo chemistry solver to convergence. Dashed lines (directly underneath the solid lines) show the analytical solution using the same rates. Dotted lines show the analytical solution using the rates of Cen (1992)."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f18", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f18", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f18_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f18", "figure_label": "Figure 18.", "figure_caption": "Photo-evaporation of a dense clump using the Moray ray-tracing module. Left panel: line cuts in the axis from the point source to the clump center at <italic>t</italic> &equals; 1, 5, 10, 15&nbsp;Myr (clockwise from the upper-left side) of the density, temperature, pressure, and neutral fraction. Right panel: volume-weighted probability distribution functions for the temperature (left-hand panel) and flow Mach number (right-hand panel) at <italic>t</italic> &equals; 10&thinsp;Myr."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f19", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f19", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f19_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f19", "figure_label": "Figure 19.", "figure_caption": "Photo-evaporation of a dense clump using the Moray ray-tracing module. Clockwise from the upper left: slices through the clump center of density, temperature, neutral hydrogen fraction, and pressure at <italic>t</italic> &equals; 10&nbsp;Myr after the initialization of the simulation. A point source of radiation is at the center of the &minus;<italic>x</italic> boundary and illuminates the clump with a constant luminosity, casting a clear shadow behind the clump, as seen in the neutral hydrogen fraction."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f20", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f20", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f20_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f20", "figure_label": "Figure 20.", "figure_caption": "Ionized fraction profiles and I-front location history for the propagation of an ionization front in an expanding universe, using Enzo&apos;s flux-limited diffusion radiation transport method. Left panel: profiles of the H&thinsp;<sc>i</sc> and H&thinsp;<sc>ii</sc> fractions (blue and red lines, respectively) at redshifts <italic>z</italic> &equals; &lcub;6.24,&thinsp;2.29,&thinsp;1.02&rcub; (solid, dashed, dot-dashed lines). Right panel: ratio of the I-front and Str&ouml;mgren radii as a function of scaled redshift in the test problem (blue solid line) and analytical solution (red dashed line)."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f21", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f21", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f21_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f21", "figure_label": "Figure 21.", "figure_caption": "Two-dimensional anisotropic conduction test in a uniform, constant temperature background with circular magnetic fields (indicated by white streamlines) centered on (0.5, 0.5) in a 256 &times; 256 grid. The background medium has a density of 1 proton&sol;cc and a temperature of 10<sup>6</sup>&nbsp;K. At <italic>t</italic> &equals; 0 (left panel), a Gaussian heat pulse is injected at (0.75, 0.5) with an FWHM of 1&sol;64 (with all numbers given in units of the box size) and a peak temperature of 10<sup>8</sup>&nbsp;K, and allowed to evolve without hydrodynamical motion (i.e., static gas) and no radiative cooling for 300&nbsp;Myr. At <italic>t</italic> &equals;&nbsp;300&nbsp;Myr (right panel), heat has been transported along magnetic field lines with no significant diffusion perpendicular to field lines. Furthermore, there are no detectable oscillations in the temperature in regions where the magnetic field is not parallel with the grids."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f22", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f22", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f22_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f22", "figure_label": "Figure 22.", "figure_caption": "Enzo weak scaling performance for a set of Ly&alpha; forest cosmology simulations with constant comoving spatial resolution per grid cell, showing cell updates per second per processor plotted as a function of the number of root grid tiles of dimension 128<sup>3</sup> (<italic>R</italic>) in each dimension. The number of MPI tasks is <italic>N</italic> &equals; <italic>R</italic><sup>3</sup>, so <italic>R</italic>&nbsp;&equals; 16 on this plot corresponds to a 2048<sup>3</sup> computational mesh running on 4096 MPI tasks. This plot goes from <italic>R</italic> &equals; 2 (8 MPI tasks) to <italic>R</italic> &equals; 24 (13,824 MPI tasks) on two supercomputers&mdash;NICS Kraken and ORNL Jaguar when they were Cray XT4 systems&mdash;and using 1, 2 or 4 MPI processes per node, where each compute node contained a single quad-core AMD Opteron CPU with a speed of 2.1&nbsp;GHz on Jaguar and 2.3&nbsp;GHz on Kraken."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f23", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f23", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f23_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f23", "figure_label": "Figure 23.", "figure_caption": "Left: strong scaling test of a 512<sup>3</sup> AMR cosmological calculation. The root grid scaling is not representative of the true strong scaling of Enzo because the root grid tiles are not repartitioned when a simulation is restarted with additional cores. The weak scaling test in Figure 22 is more representative of the scaling on the root level. The performance in the refined levels show good strong scaling up to 2048 cores. Right: time spent in representative major routines in the same AMR calculation."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f24", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f24", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f24_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f24", "figure_label": "Figure 24.", "figure_caption": "This figure shows (clockwise from upper left), the covering fraction <italic>f<sub>l</sub></italic> of the grids on a given level <italic>l</italic>, the ratio of <italic>f<sub>l</sub></italic>&sol;<italic>f</italic><sub><italic>l</italic> &plus; 1</sub>, the relative memory usage of each level (normalized by the memory usage of level 0), and, in the lower-left panel, the relative CPU usage of each level, again normalized by <italic>l</italic> &equals; 0. In each panel, three curves are shown: the solid black and long dashed red are two cosmological simulations with box sizes of 30&nbsp;h<sup>&minus;1</sup>&nbsp;Mpc and&nbsp;80&thinsp;h<sup>&minus;1</sup>&nbsp;Mpc respectively. The dot-dashed blue line is for a non-cosmological simulation of a ram-pressure stripped galaxy. In the top-right panel, there is a line at the critical ratio of 0.06, which determines if the next finer level (<italic>l</italic> &plus; 1) takes more (above) or less (below) CPU time than level <italic>l</italic>."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs490394f25", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs490394f25", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/211/2/19/apjs490394f25_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs490394f25", "figure_label": "Figure 25.", "figure_caption": "Weak scaling performance of MHD turbulence using the Dedner MHD algorithm, which has both CPU and GPU solvers. Each node of the machine (a Cray XK6) contains one 16-core AMD Opteron 6272 CPU and 1 NVIDIA Tesla K20 GPU. In this test, there are 256<sup>3</sup> cells&sol;node. The <italic>y</italic>-axis shows cell updates per second per node, which for ideal weak scaling is a horizontal line. Blue line: CPU solver. Red line: GPU solver."}]	2015-03-19 11:49:50.001304
