re above the locus include AGNs (e.g., NGC&nbsp;1275), galaxies with ice absorption at &sim;3&thinsp;&mu;m (e.g., NGC&nbsp;2623, IC 4553) and galaxies with hot dust emission (e.g., UGCA 166)."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs492953f8", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs492953f8", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/212/2/18/apjs492953f8_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs492953f8", "figure_label": "Figure 8.", "figure_caption": "Multiplicative factors used to rescale the optical spectra to match the <italic>g</italic>-band photometry. The optical spectra from Gavazzi et al. (2004) are not absolute flux calibrated so they are not included in this plot. There is a systematic offset of approximately 10&percnt;, with larger offsets seen for brighter and more extended galaxies. For large galaxies, the background may be over-subtracted due to the background estimate including some galaxy light. Star formation rate indicators calibrated with these spectra (without renormalization) will underestimate the true star formation rate by 10&percnt; or more."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs492953f9", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs492953f9", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/212/2/18/apjs492953f9_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs492953f9", "figure_label": "Figure 9.", "figure_caption": "NGC&nbsp;584 and NGC&nbsp;694 observed spectra (black), best-fit MAGPHYS models (gray), and photometry (red dots). While the MAGPHYS models approximate the observed spectra of these galaxies, they show significant differences that must be mitigated to produce smooth continuous spectra. The MAGPHYS models can disagree with the observed mid-infrared spectra of galaxies, as our photometry does not accurately constrain the dust temperatures of our galaxies."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs492953f10", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs492953f10", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/212/2/18/apjs492953f10_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs492953f10", "figure_label": "Figure 10.", "figure_caption": "Offsets between the observed and synthesized 5.8&thinsp;&mu;m photometry of galaxies. The 5.8&thinsp;&mu;m photometry of star-forming galaxies is systematically brighter than the spectroscopy, but we have not (unambiguously) identified the cause of this offset."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs492953f11", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs492953f11", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/212/2/18/apjs492953f11_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs492953f11", "figure_label": "Figure 11.", "figure_caption": "Spectra of NGC&nbsp;337, NGC&nbsp;4125, NGC&nbsp;5953, and UGCA 219. Observed spectra are shown in black, MAGPHYS models are shown in gray, and photometry used to constrain and verify the spectra are shown with red dots. These galaxies are drawn from the illustrative subset of the sample described in Appendix&nbsp;A."}, {"images": [{"image_id": "apjs492953f12", "highres": "http://www.astroexplorer.org/details/apjs492953f12", "thumbnail": "https://s3.amazonaws.com/aasie/images/0067-0049/212/2/18/apjs492953f12_tb.jpg", "format": "jpg"}], "figure_id": "apjs492953f12", "figure_label": "Figure 12.", "figure_caption": "Our spectrum of IC 4553 (Arp 220) shown with IC 4553 template spectra taken from Chary &amp; Elbaz (2001), Donley et al. (2007), Polletta et al. (2007), and Rieke et al. (2009). To aid comparisons, the spectra have been normalized at 6000&thinsp;&Aring; and our photometry is plotted with red dots. As noted by Chary &amp; Elbaz (2001), some LIRG and ULIRG SEDs from the literature were not constrained in the ultraviolet and consequently we see large differences between the templates at 2000 &Aring;. The templates show significant differences across the entire wavelength range, and these differences could impact interpretations of galaxy